@flexiarg peripherals/canonical-typed-event-vs-side-channel
@title Canonical Typed Event vs Side Channel
@sigils [📜/典]
@audience peripheral designers, transport implementers, event-schema maintainers
@tone foundational
@style pattern
@keywords event-schema, typed-event, side-channel, taxonomy, extension, WS, MUSN, frame, first-class, canonical, drift
@references [peripherals/read-existing-seam-before-implementing peripherals/split-transport-from-embodiment peripherals/progress-heartbeat-distinct-from-cycle-completion realtime/structured-events-only realtime/single-line-transport]

! conclusion: When a peripheral needs to emit or consume something the canonical event taxonomy does not yet describe, extend the taxonomy with a first-class typed event. Do not invent a side channel that bypasses the taxonomy, even if the side channel is cheaper to ship.

  + context: You are wiring a peripheral that needs to communicate something
    the existing transport (WS pipeline, drawbridge, MUSN events) does not
    have an event type for: cursor position, heartbeat, consent ack,
    bell payload metadata.

  + IF:
    The canonical transport has a typed event taxonomy — a finite,
    documented set of event shapes that consumers parse and dispatch on.

  + HOWEVER:
    Adding a new event type to the canonical taxonomy requires:
    schema authoring, consumer awareness, documentation, maybe a
    versioning step. It feels heavy. The lightweight alternative is
    obvious: open a second channel (a sidecar WebSocket, a polling
    HTTP endpoint, a file-watch, an out-of-band timer) that carries
    the new thing, with no need to touch the canonical taxonomy.

    The side channel ships in an hour. The taxonomy extension takes
    half a day. The temptation is overwhelming.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - Two-channel reality: the peripheral now lives in two places at
        once. Consumers must subscribe to both to get the full picture.
        Diagnostics fragment across both. Tooling that knew one channel
        doesn't know the other.
      - Schema-drift-by-default: the side channel has no taxonomy
        discipline, so its payload shape drifts freely. Three months
        later, no one knows what shapes are emitted on it.
      - Consent-bypass-by-accident: the canonical transport has consent
        and write-ownership boundaries baked in. The side channel
        doesn't. Now the peripheral can write things it never had
        permission to write, because the permission check lived on the
        path it bypassed.
      - Observability-bypass: telemetry, audit logging, and replay
        tooling instrument the canonical transport. The side channel
        is invisible to them. When something goes wrong on the side
        channel, there is no record.
      - "Temporary"-as-permanent: the side channel was supposed to be
        moved into the taxonomy "later." Later never comes. The temp
        is now load-bearing.

  + THEN:
    When the peripheral needs a new event, extend the taxonomy:

    1. **Author the event schema as a first-class type** in the
       canonical taxonomy. Give it a name, a payload shape, semantics,
       and a producer/consumer note. The schema lives in the same
       place all other event schemas live.
    2. **Add the producer** (the peripheral emits the event on the
       canonical transport, not on a sidecar).
    3. **Document the consumer contract** even if there is only one
       consumer today. The discipline of writing the contract makes
       future second consumers possible.
    4. **Update the taxonomy index/docs** so the next reader can find
       the event by searching the taxonomy, not by reading the
       peripheral's source.
    5. **Consume via the same subscription mechanism** other consumers
       use — same dispatch, same filtering, same backpressure
       handling, same audit trail.

    If the taxonomy extension is genuinely too heavy for the change at
    hand, that is itself a signal: the taxonomy may be over-formalised
    or under-tooled. Fix THAT (lower the cost of adding a typed event),
    rather than routing around it.

  + BECAUSE:
    A taxonomy is an institution in Ostrom's sense — a shared resource
    governed by rules-in-use. Side channels are tragedy-of-the-commons
    moves: each one is locally cheap, and each one degrades the
    institutional value of the taxonomy. Once the taxonomy is no longer
    a complete description of what flows, it stops being trusted as a
    contract; once it stops being a contract, every new consumer must
    discover what flows empirically; once that becomes normal, the
    taxonomy is dead documentation and the wire is a free-for-all.

    Typed events have non-obvious downstream value: replay tooling can
    deterministically rebuild state from the event log; new consumers
    can subscribe without coordination; backpressure and prioritisation
    can be implemented uniformly. Every side channel forecloses on
    these capabilities for the data it carries.

    The pattern also closes a peripheral-design loop. Heartbeat
    (peripherals/progress-heartbeat-distinct-from-cycle-completion) is
    exactly the case: the watchdog needs a liveness signal distinct
    from cycle events. The wrong move is a separate ping mechanism.
    The right move is to add a "heartbeat" typed event to the same
    transport, so watchdogs subscribe to the same wire as everything
    else.

    The pattern is also the principled defence against the "lightweight"
    euphemism (feedback_lightweight_euphemism, agent memory): a
    "lightweight side channel" is the precise shape of work that
    appears done but isn't institutionalised. Translation: it is a typed
    event missing its taxonomy entry.

    + evidence: M-emacs-cursor-peripheral (2026-05-24, codex-8): the
      original sketch had cursor positions broadcast on a parallel WS
      channel. Codex identified this as a side-channel against the
      canonical WS transport, and proposed adding a typed
      "cursor-position" (and later, full "presence") event to the
      canonical event taxonomy instead. The WS pipeline already had
      backpressure, audit, and consent semantics; the side channel
      would have had none.

    + evidence: realtime/structured-events-only (futon3 pattern
      library): "All inter-agent communication MUST be structured
      events with documented schemas." This pattern is the peripheral-
      design corollary: when extending a stack with new communication,
      extend the taxonomy.

    + evidence: WM API surface (futon3c, 2026-05-23 consolidation):
      War Machine surfaces (R-Criterion status, R12 apparatus, etc.)
      are all served via the canonical /api/alpha/war-machine endpoints
      on port 7070. The Emacs *War Machine* buffer and the web UI both
      consume from the same canonical endpoints; no side channel for
      "Emacs-specific" markdown vs "web-specific" JSON. The single
      canonical surface enabled both clients without divergence.

    + evidence: bell payload schema standardisation (claude-10's
      parked substrate-creation thread, 2026-05-23/24): exactly the
      case where bell payloads were drifting in shape across producers.
      Standardisation = taxonomy formalisation. The fact that the
      thread exists is evidence that side-channel-like drift had begun.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Maintain a single canonical event-taxonomy document per transport.
      Every typed event lives there.
    - Make taxonomy extension cheap: a template for new event schemas,
      a quick-add path that doesn't require ceremony. Cost-of-extension
      should not be the reason side channels exist.
    - When reviewing a peripheral mission, ask: "what new events does
      this peripheral introduce? Where in the taxonomy do they live?"
      If the answer is "they don't, we just emit them," the mission
      needs revision.
    - For M-war-machine-pilot specifically: every event the WM
      peripheral emits (cycle phase changes, judgement events,
      heartbeats, consent acks, bell payloads) must have an entry in
      the canonical event taxonomy. The Pair-stage and Collaborate-
      stage consent acks especially must be typed events, because
      consent decisions are exactly the data future audit tools will
      replay.
    - Cross-link: peripherals/split-transport-from-embodiment — typed
      events are how the transport layer stays describable
      independently of any embodiment.
